1) DRY – “Don’t Repeat Yourself" , Convention over Configuration, REST

2) Rails provides a full stack of components for creating web applications, including:

	Action Controller	- manages controllers
	Action View			- manages views
	Active Record		- base for models
	Active Resource		- managing the connection between business objects an RESTful web services
	Railties			- Railties is the core Rails code that builds new Rails applications

3) "Tweet.find(3)" ---> Will go fetch "tweets" table for id 3

4) 	C - 	t = Tweet.new
			t.key = value
			t.save
	
	R - 	Tweet.find(1,2,3)  --> will return array of tweets with id 1,2 and 3
			Tweet.where().order().find()  --> method chaining

	U - 	t = Tweet.find(2)
			t.attributes(hash)
			t.save

	D - 	t = Tweet.find(2)
			t.destroy
			Tweet.destroy_all

5) Models are saved under app/models/<name>.rb
	
	class Tweet < ActiveRecord::Base
		validates_presence_of :status    --> makes sure status to be set for all tweets
	end

6) t.errors.messages

7) Relationships in Models
	
		has_many : tweets 		--> in Zombie model 
		belongs_to :Zombie  	--> in Tweet model

	ash = Zombie.find(1)
	t = Tweet.create(status: "", zombie: ash)

8) .erb files (embedded ruby)
	<% executes whatever ruby code written here %>
	<%= prints the return value of the ruby code written here %>

	<%= link_to( text_to_show, model_instance )  %>  --> <% link_to( tweet.zombie.name , tweet.zombie)
